WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.030 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:18.910
&gt;&gt; Mary-Jane Deeb:
Welcome to the African

00:00:18.910 --> 00:00:20.920
and Middle Eastern Division.

00:00:20.920 --> 00:00:23.630
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb,
chief of the division.

00:00:23.630 --> 00:00:28.870
And I'm really delighted
to see you all here today.

00:00:28.870 --> 00:00:31.700
I'm also extremely happy

00:00:31.700 --> 00:00:37.790
to welcome Kyrgyz Ambassador
Kadyr Toktogulov to the African

00:00:37.790 --> 00:00:41.220
and Middle Eastern Division
of the Library of Congress.

00:00:41.220 --> 00:00:46.230
He has been here several times
before, however today he is here

00:00:46.230 --> 00:00:50.390
in an official capacity to
present a short documentary

00:00:50.390 --> 00:00:54.310
on Chingiz Aitmatov, the
most important Kyrgyz author

00:00:54.310 --> 00:00:56.450
of the 20th Century.

00:00:56.450 --> 00:00:59.200
Ambassador Toktogulov
was the person

00:00:59.200 --> 00:01:03.110
who originally introduced us to
today's speaker, Jeffrey Lilley.

00:01:03.110 --> 00:01:06.810
But in fact we had met
earlier ten years ago

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:12.840
when we first had a major
conference on Chingiz Aitmatov.

00:01:12.840 --> 00:01:15.740
And he was there and he
told me that he was there

00:01:15.740 --> 00:01:19.260
and he had just started
writing his book

00:01:19.260 --> 00:01:25.200
and today we're having Jeffrey
Lilly with a book completed

00:01:25.200 --> 00:01:28.980
and ready to share
with everyone here

00:01:28.980 --> 00:01:34.600
and across the world because,
as you know, we're being webcast

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:36.380
and therefore this
program is going

00:01:36.380 --> 00:01:39.620
to appear around the world.

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:44.600
And the book with
the wonderful title,

00:01:44.600 --> 00:01:46.350
"Have the Mountains Fallen?"

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:47.650
It's an intriguing title.

00:01:47.650 --> 00:01:49.340
I want to hear more about it.

00:01:49.340 --> 00:01:53.300
It will be on sale
after this program.

00:01:53.300 --> 00:01:58.480
Now a few worlds about
Ambassador Kadyr Toktogulov --

00:01:58.480 --> 00:01:59.790
On December 31,

00:01:59.790 --> 00:02:07.370
2014 Kyrgyzstan's President
Almazbek Atambaev appointed him

00:02:07.370 --> 00:02:10.610
as Ambassador Extraordinary
and Plenipotentiary

00:02:10.610 --> 00:02:15.030
of the Kyrgyz Republic to
the United States of America.

00:02:15.030 --> 00:02:17.250
And two months later
on February 23,

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:20.950
2015 he presented
his credentials

00:02:20.950 --> 00:02:24.690
to President Barack
Obama and took office.

00:02:24.690 --> 00:02:26.600
However that was not all.

00:02:26.600 --> 00:02:28.650
The following year
on February 24,

00:02:28.650 --> 00:02:33.430
2016 Kadyr Toktogulov
was again appointed

00:02:33.430 --> 00:02:39.050
by President Almazbek Atambaev
as Ambassador Extraordinary

00:02:39.050 --> 00:02:43.690
and Plenipotentiary
to Canada this time,

00:02:43.690 --> 00:02:46.950
but as he could not
divide himself into two,

00:02:46.950 --> 00:02:50.170
his residence is
officially in Washington D.C.

00:02:50.170 --> 00:02:52.790
So he presented his credentials
to the Governor General

00:02:52.790 --> 00:02:57.550
of Canada David Johnston
on March 22, 2016.

00:02:57.550 --> 00:03:00.480
We're thus very honored
today to have

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:04.370
with us two Ambassadors
in one person.

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:08.600
So we are delighted
to welcome him here.

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:10.790
Prior to his appointment
as Ambassador,

00:03:10.790 --> 00:03:12.940
Kadyr Toktogulov served

00:03:12.940 --> 00:03:17.470
as President Atambaev's Press
Secretary having worked earlier

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:20.370
as the Chief of Information
Policy in the Office

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:22.870
of the Prime Minister
of Kyrgyzstan.

00:03:22.870 --> 00:03:25.670
There he was in charge of
coordinating media relations

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:28.190
for the Prime Minister,
his deputies,

00:03:28.190 --> 00:03:31.230
and key government officials.

00:03:31.230 --> 00:03:33.400
He also coordinated
media coverage

00:03:33.400 --> 00:03:36.000
of the work of the government.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.850
Ambassador Kadyr Toktogulov
is also a very experienced

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:42.530
journalist, having
worked as a correspondent

00:03:42.530 --> 00:03:47.190
for the Associated Press
between 2003 and 2006,

00:03:47.190 --> 00:03:51.540
the Dow Jones Newswires, as well
has having contributed a number

00:03:51.540 --> 00:03:58.830
of stories for the Wall Street
Journal between 2006 and 2011.

00:03:58.830 --> 00:04:01.370
He holds a BA degree
in Journalism

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:04.880
and Mass Communications
from the American University

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:08.520
of Central Asia,
Bishkek, Kyrgyzstan,

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:12.300
and was an exchange student
at Ankara University, Ankara,

00:04:12.300 --> 00:04:20.380
Turkey, 1998 and 1999 and also
at Ithaca College between 2001

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:23.290
and 2002, here in New York.

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:25.620
So in addition to
Kyrgyz he's fluent

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:28.730
in Russian, English,
and Turkish.

00:04:28.730 --> 00:04:31.450
And now let us all
welcome the Ambassador

00:04:31.450 --> 00:04:33.510
who will introduce
a film for today.

00:04:33.510 --> 00:04:43.470
[ Applause ]

00:04:43.470 --> 00:04:44.770
&gt;&gt; Kadyr Toktogulov:
Thank you very much

00:04:44.770 --> 00:04:48.480
for this very generous
introduction Dr. Mary-Jane Deeb.

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:51.070
Dear friends it's wonderful
to see you all today

00:04:51.070 --> 00:04:53.420
at the book launch of
the newly released book

00:04:53.420 --> 00:04:54.810
by my friend Jeff Lilley.

00:04:54.810 --> 00:04:57.320
We've spoken earlier
today to figure

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.340
out what year we actually met
in Kyrgyzstan and we figured

00:05:01.340 --> 00:05:04.100
out it was 2005 in Bishkek.

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:06.540
Before I speak about
today's event and the book

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:08.300
and the author, Jeff Lilley,

00:05:08.300 --> 00:05:10.230
I'd like to express
my deepest gratitude

00:05:10.230 --> 00:05:12.490
to the Library of Congress.

00:05:12.490 --> 00:05:15.350
It's a very special institution
that holds a unique importance

00:05:15.350 --> 00:05:18.450
for the United States
and the world libraries.

00:05:18.450 --> 00:05:21.260
Special thanks to the African
and Middle Eastern Division,

00:05:21.260 --> 00:05:24.050
Chief of the Division
Dr. Mary-Jane Deeb

00:05:24.050 --> 00:05:29.320
and Joan Weeks Head Near East
Section and Turkish Specialist.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:31.570
Thank you very much for
hosting today's event.

00:05:31.570 --> 00:05:34.630
My embassy colleagues and I
have enjoyed working with you

00:05:34.630 --> 00:05:37.500
on putting together
this book presentation.

00:05:37.500 --> 00:05:40.970
I especially enjoyed our
conversations about the vast --

00:05:46.340 --> 00:05:48.400
I especially enjoyed
our conversations

00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:51.100
about the vast collection
of Central Asian literature

00:05:51.100 --> 00:05:52.490
that the Library holds.

00:05:52.490 --> 00:05:55.380
And the best moments of our
discussions were talking

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:57.520
about my home country Kyrgyzstan

00:05:57.520 --> 00:06:00.650
and our most famous writer
the late Chingiz Aitmatov.

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:03.840
I'm grateful to the Library
and to you Dr. Mary-Jane Deeb

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:06.980
and Joan Weeks for agreeing
to host the presentation

00:06:06.980 --> 00:06:10.500
of this fascinating book,
"Have the Mountains?"

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:14.140
You told me you liked the title
of the book [laughs] back then

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:17.350
when we were discussing the
details of today's event

00:06:17.350 --> 00:06:19.040
and I really like it too.

00:06:19.040 --> 00:06:21.160
I was a journalist
when Jeff and I met.

00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:23.320
He was working in Bishkek
as the Country Director

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:28.150
of the International Republican
Institute in Bishkek Office.

00:06:28.150 --> 00:06:29.750
He recently returned
to Kyrgyzstan

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:32.110
to continue his support
for my country

00:06:32.110 --> 00:06:34.550
and my country's
democratic development.

00:06:34.550 --> 00:06:36.630
The book is really fascinating.

00:06:36.630 --> 00:06:40.200
It's my country's journey to
independence through the stories

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:42.910
of its two outstanding
sons that had lived

00:06:42.910 --> 00:06:44.990
through Kyrgyz nation's
tragedies

00:06:44.990 --> 00:06:48.170
in the 20th Century before
the country declared its

00:06:48.170 --> 00:06:50.560
independence in 1991.

00:06:50.560 --> 00:06:52.890
I'm very happy that this
event is taking place

00:06:52.890 --> 00:06:55.220
as we celebrate the
90th birthday

00:06:55.220 --> 00:06:57.760
of our great writer
Chingiz Aitmatov.

00:06:57.760 --> 00:07:00.660
His books and stories
put Kyrgyzstan on the map

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:02.960
for many people around the world

00:07:02.960 --> 00:07:05.770
and helped my country stand
firmer in today's world.

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:10.400
I have personal stories about
the two heroes of the book

00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:12.380
that I'd like to share with you.

00:07:12.380 --> 00:07:14.380
Chingiz Aitmatov is
my favorite writer.

00:07:14.380 --> 00:07:16.440
His books kept me
awake at nights

00:07:16.440 --> 00:07:19.170
as I was reading his
stories about the lives

00:07:19.170 --> 00:07:20.750
of his characters during

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:23.420
and after the Word
War II in Kyrgyzstan.

00:07:23.420 --> 00:07:25.280
I was happy when I got
to see him in Ankara

00:07:25.280 --> 00:07:27.350
at the conference
when I was a student.

00:07:27.350 --> 00:07:30.200
I would manage to get an
autograph in a book by him

00:07:30.200 --> 00:07:31.730
that I was reading at the time.

00:07:31.730 --> 00:07:35.010
He was a great master in how
he told a story of my country

00:07:35.010 --> 00:07:36.540
and people during difficult days

00:07:36.540 --> 00:07:40.850
which tested human beings
courage, decency, kindness,

00:07:40.850 --> 00:07:43.490
generosity, and love
for the country.

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:46.450
The importance of Chingiz
Aitmatov to the Kyrgyz Republic

00:07:46.450 --> 00:07:48.960
and the Kyrgyz people
is significant.

00:07:48.960 --> 00:07:50.730
Nobody has made a
stronger contribution

00:07:50.730 --> 00:07:54.120
to today's Kyrgyzstan
self-identity than Aitmatov.

00:07:54.120 --> 00:07:57.600
This year we're celebrating the
90th birth of our great writer

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:00.560
and we see this book launch
as part of the celebrations.

00:08:00.560 --> 00:08:04.440
When I was here in
the U.S. 2001, 2002,

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:06.350
I attempted to meet
Azamat Altay.

00:08:06.350 --> 00:08:09.800
I was very much fascinated
by his personal story

00:08:09.800 --> 00:08:11.970
of his journey all the
way from Kyrgyzstan

00:08:11.970 --> 00:08:15.260
to the U.S. though the horrors
of World War II and challenges

00:08:15.260 --> 00:08:17.200
of his life in Europe.

00:08:17.200 --> 00:08:19.620
Through some Kyrgyz contacts
I managed to get hold

00:08:19.620 --> 00:08:22.720
of his home phone
number and dialed him.

00:08:22.720 --> 00:08:25.780
As Azamat Altay picked up
the phone and I spoke to him

00:08:25.780 --> 00:08:28.850
in Kyrgyz and told him
that I wanted to visit him,

00:08:28.850 --> 00:08:31.210
he gave me his home address.

00:08:31.210 --> 00:08:33.550
But back then there
were no smartphones

00:08:33.550 --> 00:08:38.100
that would guide you though
a city that you don't know.

00:08:38.100 --> 00:08:43.050
I couldn't get any tips on how
to get to Flushing Meadows.

00:08:43.050 --> 00:08:46.270
I was in New York for
a couple of days only

00:08:46.270 --> 00:08:47.820
so I failed to visit him.

00:08:47.820 --> 00:08:51.370
And to be honest I regret not
having made the efforts back

00:08:51.370 --> 00:08:53.950
then to see this great man.

00:08:53.950 --> 00:08:57.700
Jeff, you did a great job in
telling the intertwining stories

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:00.900
of Chingiz Aitmatov
and Azamat Altay.

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:04.220
And through their stories you
told a story of my country.

00:09:04.220 --> 00:09:06.890
You really took us through
the days of the Urkun,

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:09.390
the Great Tragedy and the
flight of the Kyrgyz people

00:09:09.390 --> 00:09:11.480
to China during their
violent crack

00:09:11.480 --> 00:09:14.090
down by the Soviet
Russian troops.

00:09:14.090 --> 00:09:16.050
You took us through the tragic
years of the World War II.

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:18.650
And in your book you took us

00:09:18.650 --> 00:09:21.510
through my country's
journey to independence.

00:09:21.510 --> 00:09:25.020
It's an emotional book and it's
an important book if one wants

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:26.500
to learn about the
Kyrgyz Republic

00:09:26.500 --> 00:09:28.580
and its best representatives.

00:09:28.580 --> 00:09:32.050
Chingiz Aitmatov and
Azamat Altay are among them.

00:09:32.050 --> 00:09:34.760
As Ambassador of an
independent Kyrgyzstan I'd

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:37.740
like to say thank
you for the book,

00:09:37.740 --> 00:09:41.350
for your hard work writing this
book, and your respect and love

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:45.330
for my country, my
country's people and heroes.

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:46.630
Thank you, Jeff.

00:09:46.630 --> 00:09:49.590
I really look forward to
the presentation and last

00:09:49.590 --> 00:09:52.170
but not least I'd like to
thank Venera Djumataeva,

00:09:52.170 --> 00:09:56.160
Director of Kyrgyz Service of
RFE/RL who came all the way

00:09:56.160 --> 00:10:00.240
from Prague for this
event and also helped us

00:10:00.240 --> 00:10:04.000
with the presentation by
making, producing this video

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:07.810
that we'll see that will
introduce the heroes of the book

00:10:07.810 --> 00:10:12.380
that Jeff wrote before
his presentation.

00:10:12.380 --> 00:10:14.180
Thank you.

00:10:14.180 --> 00:10:19.510
[ Applause ]

00:10:19.510 --> 00:10:28.770
