00:10:28.770 --> 00:10:31.990
&gt;&gt; Two Kyrgyz men who whose
lives were adversely affected

00:10:31.990 --> 00:10:34.360
and forever changed by
the biggest tragedies

00:10:34.360 --> 00:10:39.300
of the 20th Century -- Chingiz
Aitmatov and Azamat Altay.

00:10:39.300 --> 00:10:41.910
Two people whose lives
reflect all the political

00:10:41.910 --> 00:10:44.000
and moral lessons
of the century.

00:10:54.900 --> 00:10:57.980
Chingiz Aitmatov, the
most famous Kyrgyz writer,

00:10:57.980 --> 00:11:01.980
lost his father to Stalin's
repressive regime in 1938

00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:04.300
and only found where his
father had been executed

00:11:04.300 --> 00:11:07.380
and buried 53 years
after it occurred.

00:11:07.380 --> 00:11:10.410
Not only his father, a
promising young Kyrgyz leader,

00:11:10.410 --> 00:11:12.790
but several of his
uncles also fell victim

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:14.890
to the soviet dictatorship.

00:11:14.890 --> 00:11:18.080
Aitmatov hid his deep inner
sadness after losing his father

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:21.810
at the age of nine and dedicated
his life to educating himself

00:11:21.810 --> 00:11:24.250
and his three younger siblings.

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:27.150
He became an internationally
known whose books,

00:11:27.150 --> 00:11:28.630
which have been translated
into more

00:11:28.630 --> 00:11:33.510
than 160 languages describe the
national character, lifestyle,

00:11:33.510 --> 00:11:37.290
and existential philosophy
of the nomadic Kyrgyz people.

00:11:37.290 --> 00:11:40.340
In every book Aitmatov
created a hero

00:11:40.340 --> 00:11:42.630
who in whatever difficult
circumstances he

00:11:42.630 --> 00:11:44.860
or she was forced
to live would choose

00:11:44.860 --> 00:11:48.390
to live freely, happily,
and fully.

00:11:49.510 --> 00:13:02.500
[ Foreign Language ]

00:13:11.180 --> 00:13:12.890
&gt;&gt; The Kyrgyz author
was a supporter

00:13:12.890 --> 00:13:15.710
of Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev and advised him

00:13:15.710 --> 00:13:18.970
on the implementation of the
very first political reforms

00:13:18.970 --> 00:13:20.410
in the final years of the USSR.

00:13:20.410 --> 00:13:24.880
He was later appointed Soviet
Ambassador to Luxembourg

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:26.620
and then was Kyrgyzstan's
Ambassador

00:13:26.620 --> 00:13:29.720
to the Benelux Countries
spending the last 18 years

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:32.620
of his life in Europe,
mostly Brussels.

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:36.650
Even after his death, Aitmatov's
books and their heroes continued

00:13:36.650 --> 00:13:40.440
to introduce Kyrgyzstan as a
beautiful mountainous country

00:13:40.440 --> 00:13:44.510
and its people rich character
and values to the entire world.

00:13:44.510 --> 00:13:56.040
[ Music ]

00:13:56.040 --> 00:14:00.600
Azamat Altay, a young and
educated Kyrgyz man decided

00:14:00.600 --> 00:14:03.360
to stay in the west after
World War II after realizing

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:06.250
that he would be punished
in the USSR since serving

00:14:06.250 --> 00:14:08.130
as a POW in a Nazi Camp.

00:14:08.130 --> 00:14:11.870
That decision cut him off from
his homeland, from his father,

00:14:11.870 --> 00:14:15.250
and other relatives
for 55 years.

00:14:15.250 --> 00:14:17.160
Eager to make a connection
with his homeland,

00:14:17.160 --> 00:14:19.600
Altay made contacts
with other Russian

00:14:19.600 --> 00:14:21.340
and Soviet dissidents
living in Europe

00:14:21.340 --> 00:14:24.250
and attended several
gatherings of Central Asian,

00:14:24.250 --> 00:14:26.910
and Soviet dissident,
even writing articles

00:14:26.910 --> 00:14:29.170
for dissident publications.

00:14:29.170 --> 00:14:30.770
He was later appointed an editor

00:14:30.770 --> 00:14:32.740
of the [inaudible]
magazine published

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:35.410
by Central Asian
dissidents in Europe.

00:14:35.410 --> 00:14:38.760
Through those connections Azamat
Altay became radio for Europe,

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:41.800
Radio Liberties very
first Kyrgyz broadcaster

00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:44.170
in March 1953.

00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:47.800
It his work, Altay had to
cover many taboo topics

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:51.800
in Soviet Kyrgyzstan such as
victims of Stalin's repression,

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:53.900
young Kyrgyz writers,
intellectuals,

00:14:53.900 --> 00:14:57.560
poets and politicians whose
names let alone their works were

00:14:57.560 --> 00:15:00.320
forbidden in the Kyrgyz
media at the time.

00:15:00.320 --> 00:15:02.940
Alta, and later his
new Kyrgyz colleagues

00:15:02.940 --> 00:15:06.790
at RFE/RL covered issues
regarding the Kyrgyz diaspora

00:15:06.790 --> 00:15:10.110
living in Afghanistan,
Turkey, and Pakistan.

00:15:10.110 --> 00:15:12.930
RFE/RLs Kyrgyz service also
paid a lot of attention

00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:15.950
in the early years to
Kyrgyz language, customs,

00:15:15.950 --> 00:15:18.930
and history issues in the
ever increasingly Russified

00:15:18.930 --> 00:15:20.230
Soviet Kyrgyzstan.

00:15:20.230 --> 00:15:24.560
Azamat Altay collected some
6,000 books and magazines

00:15:24.560 --> 00:15:27.160
on Kyrgyz and Central
Asian topics at his home

00:15:27.160 --> 00:15:30.160
and had helped some
prominent western academics

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:31.460
to conduct their research

00:15:31.460 --> 00:15:34.750
on Kyrgyzstan behind
the iron curtain.

00:15:34.750 --> 00:15:38.900
He reported for RFE/RL Kyrgyz
service for some 40 years.

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:43.000
Attacked regularly by the
Soviet Kyrgyz media as a traitor

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.530
and enemy of the people,

00:15:44.530 --> 00:15:47.550
Azamat Altay still had
his secret supporters

00:15:47.550 --> 00:15:49.810
and admirers in Kyrgyzstan.

00:15:49.810 --> 00:15:52.280
Intellectuals, writers,
and scholars would listen

00:15:52.280 --> 00:15:54.060
to RFE/RL Kyrgyz programs

00:15:54.060 --> 00:15:58.500
at their dachas often built
atop hills with better reception

00:15:58.500 --> 00:16:00.340
and they would discuss
Altay himself

00:16:00.340 --> 00:16:04.740
and RFE/RL Kyrgyz service
programs among themselves.

00:16:04.740 --> 00:16:06.040
Some of the topics were related

00:16:06.040 --> 00:16:08.020
to the Soviet Communist
Leadership

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:09.480
and political corruption issues.

00:16:09.480 --> 00:16:14.730
That's why in 1995 when Altay,
a retired veteran journalist

00:16:14.730 --> 00:16:18.660
and former RFE/RL Kyrgyz Service
Director was finally invited

00:16:18.660 --> 00:16:22.530
to independent Kyrgyzstan and
arrived in the Capital Bishkek,

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:26.070
he was greeted as a national
hero as a Kyrgyz American

00:16:26.070 --> 00:16:28.550
who had devoted his
life to the struggle

00:16:28.550 --> 00:16:31.200
for his people's
freedom and independence.

00:16:31.200 --> 00:16:36.510
For Kyrgyz language,
culture, and history.

