00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.510
"Have the Mountains Fallen?"

00:24:32.510 --> 00:24:35.880
is a story of the Cold War
from the other side with roots

00:24:35.880 --> 00:24:38.000
in the 1920s and '30s

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.380
when Soviet power was
establishing itself

00:24:40.380 --> 00:24:42.980
across the Eurasian landmass.

00:24:42.980 --> 00:24:46.080
It tells the parallel
stories of Aitmatov and Altay,

00:24:46.080 --> 00:24:49.850
two men who travel separately
though life until they meet

00:24:49.850 --> 00:24:54.790
and find common cause, in of all
places New York City in 1975.

00:24:54.790 --> 00:24:56.380
Their life stories
are testaments

00:24:56.380 --> 00:24:59.000
to the human spirit's
quest for freedom.

00:24:59.000 --> 00:25:02.550
Their lives are proof that
lives live only for so long.

00:25:02.550 --> 00:25:05.550
That truth, as evidence by
the attainment of justice

00:25:05.550 --> 00:25:08.630
and redemption is
achievable and that the search

00:25:08.630 --> 00:25:13.190
for a meaningful life is
based on individual freedom.

00:25:13.190 --> 00:25:17.260
So everybody is familiar
with Kyrgyzstan country,

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:21.530
descended from nomads, 90%
mountains, and home to some

00:25:21.530 --> 00:25:25.190
of the most beautiful and
pristine nature in the world,

00:25:25.190 --> 00:25:28.420
as you can see from
the cover of the book,

00:25:28.420 --> 00:25:30.140
which is actually
my wife's photo.

00:25:30.140 --> 00:25:32.610
My wife is a photographer
and she's here today.

00:25:32.610 --> 00:25:33.910
And we thought we
could do better

00:25:33.910 --> 00:25:36.870
than Indiana University Press,
which got a beautiful photo

00:25:36.870 --> 00:25:39.790
but my wife's was better.

00:25:39.790 --> 00:25:42.710
So let's move on.

00:25:42.710 --> 00:25:45.280
Like so many other
citizens, this is a picture

00:25:45.280 --> 00:25:47.820
of Torekul Aitmatov,
Chingiz Aitmatov's father

00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:49.710
and a young Chingiz
when he was probably

00:25:49.710 --> 00:25:52.420
about two years old in 1930.

00:25:52.420 --> 00:25:55.840
Like so many other citizens
at that time, Azamat Altay

00:25:55.840 --> 00:25:59.180
and Chingiz Aitmatov's
father pictured here,

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:01.900
believed in Soviet power
which had brought literacy,

00:26:01.900 --> 00:26:06.130
electricity, hospitals and
schools to the Kyrgyz people.

00:26:06.130 --> 00:26:09.180
They served it loyally until
Stalin's terror started

00:26:09.180 --> 00:26:12.850
to wreak havoc across the
Soviet Union in the 1930s.

00:26:12.850 --> 00:26:17.500
The purges swept up
Torekul Aitmatov in 1938.

00:26:17.500 --> 00:26:22.600
Train station, there's a
vivid scene in the book

00:26:22.600 --> 00:26:25.080
where Chingiz Aitmatov
says goodbye to his father

00:26:25.080 --> 00:26:27.160
and not even knowing that
he'll never see him again

00:26:27.160 --> 00:26:30.930
on the train station in Moscow.

00:26:30.930 --> 00:26:37.070
Those purges made a
disbeliever out of Azamat Altay

00:26:37.070 --> 00:26:41.100
and they shape Chingiz
Aitmatov's life.

00:26:41.100 --> 00:26:46.040
World War II was a crucible for
both Altay and Chingiz Aitmatov.

00:26:46.040 --> 00:26:48.210
They were eight years
separated, the men.

00:26:48.210 --> 00:26:49.700
Altay was born in 1920.

00:26:49.700 --> 00:26:51.730
Chingiz Aitmatov
was born in 1928.

00:26:51.730 --> 00:26:56.340
So by the time World War II
happened in the Soviet Union,

00:26:56.340 --> 00:26:58.130
they were both young men.

00:26:58.130 --> 00:27:01.780
As a 14-year-old in a
village bereft of men

00:27:01.780 --> 00:27:05.480
because they had all
been called to the front,

00:27:05.480 --> 00:27:07.870
Chingiz Aitmatov
delivered death notices

00:27:07.870 --> 00:27:11.310
to families whose fathers, sons,
or uncles had died in the war.

00:27:11.310 --> 00:27:17.150
So I want to read you a little
passage from the book on that.

00:27:20.400 --> 00:27:23.400
So Chingiz Aitmatov has just
delivered a death notice

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:25.000
to a family.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:27.930
Chingiz would then stare at
the ground uncomfortable,

00:27:27.930 --> 00:27:30.530
14 years old, shifting his feet.

00:27:30.530 --> 00:27:32.910
Usually he would hear a
heavy sigh from the mother,

00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:34.800
then whimpering or heaving,

00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:38.120
and finally crying would rend
the air like a plate shattering.

00:27:38.120 --> 00:27:40.890
Chingiz would stand there a
young boy with nowhere to run

00:27:40.890 --> 00:27:43.430
and no way to console.

00:27:43.430 --> 00:27:45.920
Villagers began associating
the young village assistant

00:27:45.920 --> 00:27:47.220
with bad luck.

00:27:47.220 --> 00:27:48.840
As soon as households
saw him riding

00:27:48.840 --> 00:27:51.900
down the street they would
shun him like an evil spirit.

00:27:51.900 --> 00:27:54.900
"Don't come to our house,"
they would say, "Pass by.

00:27:54.900 --> 00:27:56.670
Don't bring us bad news."

00:27:56.670 --> 00:28:00.310
Such a young boy shouldering
such heavy responsibilities

00:28:00.310 --> 00:28:03.530
to suffer the village's grief
as the messenger of bad news,

00:28:03.530 --> 00:28:06.810
a piece of paper in
exchange for a son.

00:28:06.810 --> 00:28:09.860
But this was how Soviet Society
endured during World War II

00:28:09.860 --> 00:28:13.790
or the Great Patriotic War
as it is known in Russian.

00:28:13.790 --> 00:28:16.610
Ironies overwhelm, the
distant war reeking havoc

00:28:16.610 --> 00:28:18.490
in an isolated village,

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:21.820
teenagers running village
affairs and a boy not big enough

00:28:21.820 --> 00:28:24.470
to mount his horse
delivering death sentences --

00:28:24.470 --> 00:28:28.110
not death sentences,
death notices.

00:28:28.110 --> 00:28:32.200
Meanwhile Soviet conscript Altay
was scrambling for his life

00:28:32.200 --> 00:28:35.930
after being overrun by the
German Blitzkrieg in June 1941.

00:28:35.930 --> 00:28:38.150
He was serving in
Soviet occupied Lithuania

00:28:38.150 --> 00:28:39.900
at that point.

00:28:39.900 --> 00:28:43.690
Altay escaped from Nazi
POW camps not once,

00:28:43.690 --> 00:28:45.380
not twice, but three times.

00:28:45.380 --> 00:28:47.260
Eventually joining
French Freedom Fighters

00:28:47.260 --> 00:28:49.790
on the march to liberate Paris.

00:28:49.790 --> 00:28:52.770
He dreamed of returning to
his home village on Issyk-Kul,

00:28:52.770 --> 00:28:56.530
you saw that, but Soviet
Leader Stalin's perverse logic

00:28:56.530 --> 00:28:59.830
considered Soviet
POWs as traitors just

00:28:59.830 --> 00:29:03.660
because they had the
misfortune to be captured alive.

00:29:03.660 --> 00:29:07.220
That meant prison camp in
Siberia for someone like Altay,

00:29:07.220 --> 00:29:09.590
even though he had
crisscrossed Europe fighting

00:29:09.590 --> 00:29:13.500
for his own survival and
always opposing the Nazis.

00:29:13.500 --> 00:29:16.040
It was absurd.

00:29:16.040 --> 00:29:17.540
Altay ended up making a decision

00:29:17.540 --> 00:29:20.840
which irrevocably
change his life.

00:29:20.840 --> 00:29:22.870
After midnight on --
this is from the book --

00:29:22.870 --> 00:29:26.830
After midnight on January
1st, 1946 Altay was serving

00:29:26.830 --> 00:29:28.850
as a Soviet border guard then --

00:29:28.850 --> 00:29:30.150
as revelers and cities

00:29:30.150 --> 00:29:32.390
around Europe were raising
their glasses to the end

00:29:32.390 --> 00:29:36.420
of World War II, Soviet border
guard Azamat Altay tossed aside

00:29:36.420 --> 00:29:39.970
his rifle, threw off his
military overcoat and stole

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:41.820
across the boarder
into the English zone

00:29:41.820 --> 00:29:44.160
of recently liberated Germany.

00:29:44.160 --> 00:29:47.590
Altay headed south from the
English zone in Germany,

00:29:47.590 --> 00:29:50.120
he was determined to get
to France, the only country

00:29:50.120 --> 00:29:52.080
that had welcomed him
and where he had friends

00:29:52.080 --> 00:29:53.820
from his partisan days.

00:29:53.820 --> 00:29:55.790
Using a smattering
of French, German,

00:29:55.790 --> 00:29:58.760
and Russian he begged a ticket
off an elderly station worker

00:29:58.760 --> 00:30:00.060
at the Saarbrucken
Train Station.

00:30:00.060 --> 00:30:04.700
Lacking permission to cross the
still-militarized German-French

00:30:04.700 --> 00:30:08.850
border, he stowed away, hiding
in the first-class bathroom.

00:30:08.850 --> 00:30:11.680
Altay arrived in Paris,
a free but penniless man,

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:13.650
with not a French
franc to his name.

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:16.810
A passerby gave him two
francs to ride on the subway.

00:30:16.810 --> 00:30:19.350
It was a bumble start
to a new life,

00:30:19.350 --> 00:30:23.470
but with each mile he traveled
on foot by train or subway --

00:30:23.470 --> 00:30:26.800
he was leaving behind the
tragedies of the past.

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:29.790
In Europe after the war, Altay
scrambled to make a living.

00:30:29.790 --> 00:30:32.690
He did manual labor in
small towns in France.

00:30:32.690 --> 00:30:35.910
It was a lonely time with few
friends among the rural French

00:30:35.910 --> 00:30:38.090
who had no idea where
he came from.

00:30:38.090 --> 00:30:40.850
As a matter of fact there's
this little story in the book

00:30:40.850 --> 00:30:44.840
about Altay was so
lonely that he got a dog

00:30:44.840 --> 00:30:48.010
and he would put this dog in
a cart and then he would kind

00:30:48.010 --> 00:30:50.990
of wheel the cart I guess around
the little village he was in

00:30:50.990 --> 00:30:53.430
and he named the dog
"My Friend" in Kyrgyz,

00:30:53.430 --> 00:30:55.010
which is "Menin Dosum".

00:30:55.010 --> 00:30:56.310
And they called him --

00:30:56.310 --> 00:30:59.070
the French villagers called
him "The Chinese with a dog."

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:04.450
That's the best they could get.

00:31:04.450 --> 00:31:08.150
Altay eventually educated
himself anew, immersing himself

00:31:08.150 --> 00:31:10.680
in European philosophy in
the struggle for independence

00:31:10.680 --> 00:31:12.060
of Soviet Central Asia.

00:31:12.060 --> 00:31:14.640
in 1953, as we saw in
that wonderful film,

00:31:14.640 --> 00:31:17.670
he became the voice of Radio
Liberty broadcasting back

00:31:17.670 --> 00:31:19.040
into Soviet Kyrgyzsia.

00:31:19.040 --> 00:31:20.520
So it's two parallel stories.

00:31:20.520 --> 00:31:22.850
So I'm going to be
jumping back and forth.

00:31:22.850 --> 00:31:25.930
Meanwhile, Aitmatov, scarred by
the disappearance of his father,

00:31:25.930 --> 00:31:27.960
here's Aitmatov as a
young man you can see.

00:31:27.960 --> 00:31:32.100
I guess he's to his
mother's left.

00:31:32.100 --> 00:31:35.680
And this is his brother Ilgez,
and this is his sister Roza

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:37.350
who is still alive and well.

00:31:37.350 --> 00:31:40.290
And Ilgez and Roza are both
alive and well in Bishkek

00:31:40.290 --> 00:31:44.450
in their 80s, and this is
his sister Luzia behind him.

00:31:44.450 --> 00:31:48.720
So scarred by the disappearance
of his father in 1937,

00:31:48.720 --> 00:31:51.720
Aitmatov was keeping his head
down and as the eldest male

00:31:51.720 --> 00:31:53.230
in the family, nine years old,

00:31:53.230 --> 00:31:55.200
trying to help his
family survive,

00:31:55.200 --> 00:31:57.760
he was considered the son
of an enemy of the people,

00:31:57.760 --> 00:32:02.060
denied his scholarship, refused
his stipend, and denied entrance

00:32:02.060 --> 00:32:05.310
into graduate school
despite stellar grades.

00:32:05.310 --> 00:32:07.120
He took to writing instead.

00:32:07.120 --> 00:32:10.350
He wrote stories of independent
minded fallible people

00:32:10.350 --> 00:32:13.720
who on the outside may have
been loyal Soviet citizens.

00:32:13.720 --> 00:32:17.170
But reading between the lines
his heroes bucked the system.

00:32:17.170 --> 00:32:18.940
Whether it was patriarchal
tradition,

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:21.770
Soviet ideology, or groupthink.

00:32:21.770 --> 00:32:24.860
How Aitmatov did this under
Soviet censorship is one

00:32:24.860 --> 00:32:27.410
of the most fascinating
parts of this story.

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:30.950
He contorted himself, hid
behind the Kyrgyz language,

00:32:30.950 --> 00:32:34.020
which sensors didn't
understand, and compromised

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:35.820
where and when necessary.

00:32:35.820 --> 00:32:37.660
As someone who knew
him well told me

00:32:37.660 --> 00:32:40.500
when I was researching the book,

00:32:40.500 --> 00:32:44.800
"When Chingiz Aitmatov got
behind a desk he couldn't lie."

00:32:46.810 --> 00:32:52.700
So he starts to break into
fame and be famous., in 1963,

00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:54.000
and his reputation

00:32:54.000 --> 00:32:55.940
or his family's reputation
is resurrected

00:32:55.940 --> 00:32:59.360
when he wins the Lenin
Prize of 1963 for a series

00:32:59.360 --> 00:33:03.020
of short stories, one of which
was "Jamila", who I'm sure a lot

00:33:03.020 --> 00:33:04.360
of people in this
room have read.

00:33:04.360 --> 00:33:05.660
Beautiful story.

00:33:05.660 --> 00:33:07.580
So here is a wonderful picture

00:33:07.580 --> 00:33:10.570
of Chingiz Aitmatov selling
his books at a book fair.

00:33:10.570 --> 00:33:13.190
And you can see "Jamila"
right there in the background.

00:33:13.190 --> 00:33:16.010
It was a couple of years
after "Jamila" came out.

00:33:16.010 --> 00:33:17.880
Just a neat, neat
picture that I found

00:33:17.880 --> 00:33:20.390
in the archives in Bishkek.

00:33:20.390 --> 00:33:26.930
So then Altay fearful that
Soviet spies would try

00:33:26.930 --> 00:33:29.890
to assassinate him for his
radio work, Altay immigrated

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:33.650
to the U.S. and he was one of
the first Kyrgyz ever to do so.

00:33:33.650 --> 00:33:36.980
He settled in New York
City as Kadyr knows,

00:33:36.980 --> 00:33:38.880
in Flushing Meadows, right?

00:33:38.880 --> 00:33:42.440
A melting pot of nationalities
and Cold War intrigues.

00:33:42.440 --> 00:33:44.340
And he started a
20-year career working

00:33:44.340 --> 00:33:47.330
in the New York public libraries
-- a New York public library

00:33:47.330 --> 00:33:48.630
and Columbia University Library.

00:33:48.630 --> 00:33:52.480
I think Altay would feel very at
home at the Library of Congress.

00:33:52.480 --> 00:33:54.340
I am sure he was
here many times.

00:33:54.340 --> 00:33:57.880
So now it gets neat.

00:33:57.880 --> 00:34:00.870
You have these two parallel
stories of men living

00:34:00.870 --> 00:34:03.120
and what was fascinating
to me is when I decided

00:34:03.120 --> 00:34:06.210
to incorporate Altay into the
story, which is a couple years

00:34:06.210 --> 00:34:09.940
after I had started
research Aitmatov's life,

00:34:09.940 --> 00:34:13.440
I found out the way
their lives intersected.

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:17.610
So far from home, cut off
from his family and culture,

00:34:17.610 --> 00:34:19.230
Altay suffered immensely.

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:22.220
He was a persona non grata
having been declared a traitor

00:34:22.220 --> 00:34:24.910
after jumping lines and
sentenced to 25 years

00:34:24.910 --> 00:34:27.520
in jail should he ever
return to the Soviet Union.

00:34:27.520 --> 00:34:28.820
His name was blackened

00:34:28.820 --> 00:34:31.790
by propaganda campaigns
in Soviet Kyrgyzia.

00:34:31.790 --> 00:34:34.860
His solace was music
of his homeland.

00:34:34.860 --> 00:34:38.060
Lilting melodies played on the
Kyrgyz three-string guitar,

00:34:38.060 --> 00:34:42.090
the komuz and Aitmatov's
stories, which formed part

00:34:42.090 --> 00:34:46.170
of his collection of 5,000,
6,000 books on Central Asia

00:34:46.170 --> 00:34:49.510
in his personal library
in Queens New York.

00:34:49.510 --> 00:34:53.150
So about that meeting
in 1975, in the 1970s

00:34:53.150 --> 00:34:55.600
when the two men's lives
intersected for the first time.

00:34:55.600 --> 00:34:57.090
Now this is the Cold War.

00:34:57.090 --> 00:35:00.740
Alta is persona non grata
in the Soviet Union.

00:35:00.740 --> 00:35:04.450
The KGB is alive and
strong and here's a picture

00:35:04.450 --> 00:35:05.750
of these two men meeting

00:35:05.750 --> 00:35:09.010
in Altay's apartment
in Queen's New York.

00:35:09.010 --> 00:35:12.330
So that's the American
angle to the book.

00:35:12.330 --> 00:35:14.760
During a period of warming
and U.S. Soviet relations

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:17.660
in the 1970s when
Space cooperation

00:35:17.660 --> 00:35:19.530
between the countries started

00:35:19.530 --> 00:35:21.270
and cultural exchanges
took place,

00:35:21.270 --> 00:35:23.970
we all call that detente,
we called it detente.

00:35:23.970 --> 00:35:27.140
Aitmatov got invited to the
U.S. for the performance

00:35:27.140 --> 00:35:29.900
of a play he had
written about Stalinism

00:35:29.900 --> 00:35:32.870
and the scars it had left
on the Kyrgyz people.

00:35:32.870 --> 00:35:35.260
As a big fan of Aitmatov's
works,

00:35:35.260 --> 00:35:39.730
Altay played an instrumental
role in Aitmatov getting invited

00:35:39.730 --> 00:35:41.420
by the U.S. State Department.

00:35:41.420 --> 00:35:44.070
He was very helpful
in getting the visa.

00:35:44.070 --> 00:35:46.990
The two men met in
Aitmatov's New York hotel room

00:35:46.990 --> 00:35:50.780
on the very day that Soviet and
American astronauts shook hands

00:35:50.780 --> 00:35:53.830
in space during the
Apollo-Soyuz hookup.

00:35:53.830 --> 00:35:56.080
You can't make that stuff up.

00:35:56.080 --> 00:35:59.990
And I just want to read
a passage from the book.

00:35:59.990 --> 00:36:03.030
The scene was an uncanny
terrestrial version

00:36:03.030 --> 00:36:05.880
of the nomadic events that had
happened earlier in the day.

00:36:05.880 --> 00:36:09.610
At noon New York time Apollo
had achieved a firm linkup

00:36:09.610 --> 00:36:13.040
with Soyuz over the
Atlantic Ocean 620 miles west

00:36:13.040 --> 00:36:14.340
of Portugal.

00:36:14.340 --> 00:36:16.470
In a culmination of
three years of joint work

00:36:16.470 --> 00:36:18.350
by the Cold War rivals.

00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:21.840
Soviet cosmonaut Alexey Leonov
welcomed American astronaut Tom

00:36:21.840 --> 00:36:25.180
Stafford through the hatches
with a hearty handshake.

00:36:25.180 --> 00:36:28.500
President Ford and General
Secretary Brezhnev sent

00:36:28.500 --> 00:36:31.730
congratulating messages
to the crews.

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:35.540
It Aitmatov's hotel
that evening,

00:36:35.540 --> 00:36:40.340
620 miles lower a celebratory
atmosphere prevailed

00:36:40.340 --> 00:36:42.120
but of a far different nature.

00:36:42.120 --> 00:36:44.700
The impromptu gathering
of Kyrgyz in New York,

00:36:44.700 --> 00:36:48.150
though unpublicized had
as much significance

00:36:48.150 --> 00:36:52.510
for the Kyrgyz people as did
the Apollo-Soyuz handshake,

00:36:52.510 --> 00:36:53.810
maybe even more.

00:36:53.810 --> 00:36:55.620
It represented a coming together

00:36:55.620 --> 00:36:58.170
of the disparate parts
of the Kyrgyz elite.

00:36:58.170 --> 00:37:01.290
Two leading cultural lights of
Soviet Kyrgyzia in the same room

00:37:01.290 --> 00:37:03.760
with the founding voice
of the Kyrgyz service

00:37:03.760 --> 00:37:05.600
of American's Radio Liberty.

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:08.110
A Kyrgyz Hall of
Fame, if you will.

00:37:08.110 --> 00:37:11.750
What unified then was blood,
and the simple joy of connection

00:37:11.750 --> 00:37:13.570
that stood as an affirmation

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:16.370
that the Kyrgyz people
were living, existing,

00:37:16.370 --> 00:37:20.190
and staying together, even
across ideological divides

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:22.980
that seemed insurmountable
to so many --

00:37:22.980 --> 00:37:25.390
the day's events
not withstanding.

00:37:25.390 --> 00:37:31.200
In 1979, Altay returned
to Radio Liberty in Munich

00:37:31.200 --> 00:37:33.460
and headed the Kyrgyz service.

00:37:33.460 --> 00:37:36.080
He arrived in time to
chronicle the demise

00:37:36.080 --> 00:37:39.130
of his archenemy
the Soviet Union.

00:37:39.130 --> 00:37:42.830
As the Soviet Union stumbled
into Afghanistan in the 1980s,

00:37:42.830 --> 00:37:46.150
Aitmatov's pros got stronger.

00:37:46.150 --> 00:37:48.590
Aitmatov was widely
published in the USSR

00:37:48.590 --> 00:37:52.600
and around the world
in 160 languages.

00:37:52.600 --> 00:37:55.510
But his public statements
often sang the praises

00:37:55.510 --> 00:37:57.240
of the Soviet system.

00:37:57.240 --> 00:38:01.700
That was the price of Aitmatov's
inner freedom to write his mind,

00:38:01.700 --> 00:38:03.000
to write his conscience.

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:05.110
Freedom inside had
to be purchased

00:38:05.110 --> 00:38:07.870
with compromise from
the outside.

00:38:11.190 --> 00:38:14.670
With the advent of perestroika
the two men, Azamat Altay

00:38:14.670 --> 00:38:16.800
and Chingiz Aitmatov
met more frequently

00:38:16.800 --> 00:38:21.680
with Aitmatov brushing
aside the increasingly KGB.

00:38:21.680 --> 00:38:25.020
Aitmatov was appointed a member
of Gorbachev's reform team

00:38:25.020 --> 00:38:26.780
and spoke openly about failures

00:38:26.780 --> 00:38:30.380
of the Soviet system during
perestroika and the importance

00:38:30.380 --> 00:38:32.560
of restoring the place
of language, history,

00:38:32.560 --> 00:38:34.410
and culture for the Kyrgyz

00:38:34.410 --> 00:38:37.840
and other constituent
Republics of the USSR.

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:44.100
This photo, likely from 1989
shows a relaxed gathering

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:47.360
in Munich, Kyrgyz
style, with Aitmatov,

00:38:47.360 --> 00:38:50.590
the honored guest getting
the head of the lamb.

00:38:50.590 --> 00:38:54.220
Altay, the oldest at the table
is seated to Aitmatov's left.

00:38:54.220 --> 00:38:58.940
But one meeting in particular
symbolized the new era.

00:38:58.940 --> 00:39:02.060
A time of hope and
ultimately redemption .

00:39:02.060 --> 00:39:05.760
Aitmatov was in Munich
presenting his latest book.

00:39:05.760 --> 00:39:08.890
Unbeknownst to him, Altay
and other Kyrgyz working

00:39:08.890 --> 00:39:11.620
at Radio Liberty
were in the audience.

00:39:11.620 --> 00:39:14.140
The KGB in an effort
to avoid a meeting

00:39:14.140 --> 00:39:17.470
between the two men hustled
Aitmatov and his wife Maria

00:39:17.470 --> 00:39:21.250
out of the hall and
into a waiting car.

00:39:21.250 --> 00:39:25.420
A James Bond like
car chase ensued.

00:39:25.420 --> 00:39:27.530
So this is from the book.

00:39:27.530 --> 00:39:29.700
When the car carrying
the Aimatov's arrived

00:39:29.700 --> 00:39:33.140
at their hotel a white van
pulled up right behind.

00:39:33.140 --> 00:39:34.600
Outstepped Azamat Altay

00:39:34.600 --> 00:39:37.530
with several Kyrgyz
adults and children.

00:39:37.530 --> 00:39:41.100
The wary KGB agent rushed
to block their approach

00:39:41.100 --> 00:39:43.450
but Aitmatov halted them.

00:39:43.450 --> 00:39:47.680
"These are my people.

00:39:47.680 --> 00:39:52.190
Let me speak with them."

00:39:52.190 --> 00:39:53.490
He said.

00:40:01.420 --> 00:40:05.670
Aitmatov's simple
gesture spoke volumes.

00:40:05.670 --> 00:40:09.370
It said, "That's enough."

00:40:09.370 --> 00:40:12.300
Excuse me.

00:40:12.300 --> 00:40:15.550
And with his command to
the two KGB officers fear

00:40:15.550 --> 00:40:18.640
and silence engrained in the
Kyrgyz people for decades

00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:22.070
and carried by Aitmatov
himself started to recede.

00:40:22.070 --> 00:40:25.790
It was as if Aitmatov were
saying it was time to learn how

00:40:25.790 --> 00:40:28.140
to live in a normal society.

00:40:28.140 --> 00:40:34.970
No more keeping silent, no more
fear, and no more tragedies.

00:40:34.970 --> 00:40:37.710
Yes, the fatherless
Aitmatov seemed to be saying,

00:40:37.710 --> 00:40:40.370
"Let the next generation
of Kyrgyz grow

00:40:40.370 --> 00:40:43.890
up with their fathers and
let the KGB learn another way

00:40:43.890 --> 00:40:46.400
to carry out its work.

00:40:46.400 --> 00:40:47.700
So this is a fun picture.

00:40:47.700 --> 00:40:54.390
Altay returned to Kyrgyzstan in
1995 after a 55-year absence.

00:40:54.390 --> 00:40:56.800
His criminal sentence was
abolished and he was greeted

00:40:56.800 --> 00:40:59.610
like a hero in independent
Kyrgyzstan.

00:40:59.610 --> 00:41:01.010
When he stepped off the plane

00:41:01.010 --> 00:41:03.410
onto the tarmac he
kissed the ground.

00:41:03.410 --> 00:41:07.240
There to meet him
was Chingiz Aitmatov.

00:41:07.240 --> 00:41:14.070
So you can see here Altay
is under the orange arrow,

00:41:14.070 --> 00:41:15.470
Chingiz Aitmatov
is under the blue,

00:41:15.470 --> 00:41:18.120
and under the green is
Chingiz Aitmatov's son, Askar,

00:41:18.120 --> 00:41:21.750
who is a Kyrgyz diplomat
in New York at the time,

00:41:21.750 --> 00:41:25.030
and Askar got Azamat
Altay the visa

00:41:25.030 --> 00:41:29.330
and Askar accompanied Azamat
Altay all the way back

00:41:29.330 --> 00:41:31.420
to Kyrgyzstan at a time
when there weren't --

00:41:31.420 --> 00:41:33.740
you had to go through Tashkent

00:41:33.740 --> 00:41:35.040
and wait hours, hours,
and hours.

00:41:35.040 --> 00:41:38.050
So it's really kind of neat
that the Aitmatov's were

00:41:38.050 --> 00:41:41.660
on both sides taking
care of Altay.

00:41:41.660 --> 00:41:44.050
So what are the lessons
from their lives?

00:41:44.050 --> 00:41:45.600
The individual accounts.

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:48.330
Freedom of thought, speech, and
religion are the foundations

00:41:48.330 --> 00:41:50.540
of a democratic society.

00:41:50.540 --> 00:41:53.060
And take nothing for granted.

00:41:53.060 --> 00:41:54.560
Nothing is guaranteed.

00:41:54.560 --> 00:41:57.600
Dedicate yourself to what you
believe in, structure your life

00:41:57.600 --> 00:42:00.610
to achieve it, base
decisions upon it and yes,

00:42:00.610 --> 00:42:03.980
be ready to make compromises
to achieve the larger goal,

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:06.460
and in the case of Azamat Altay,

00:42:06.460 --> 00:42:09.530
be ready to lose precious
things along the way.

00:42:09.530 --> 00:42:12.310
"The moral arc of history
bends towards justice."

00:42:12.310 --> 00:42:14.130
Martin Luther King said.

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:17.550
Both men, Azamat Altay and
Chingiz Aitmatov found justice

00:42:17.550 --> 00:42:21.270
in their lifetimes and that's
the redemption in the title.

00:42:21.270 --> 00:42:25.710
So Altay's redemption we could
see was returning to Kyrgyzstan

00:42:25.710 --> 00:42:29.590
and as we saw in that wonderful
film, being greeted like a hero

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:33.820
by his fellow countrymen
and women.

00:42:35.470 --> 00:42:40.270
A few years earlier Aitmatov
himself before Altay's return,

00:42:40.270 --> 00:42:44.200
Altay himself after decades
of looking found his father,

00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:46.600
Torekul Aitmatov was at
the bottom of a grave

00:42:46.600 --> 00:42:49.880
with 137 other skeletons
piled on top,

00:42:49.880 --> 00:42:52.240
all victims of Stalin's purges.

00:42:52.240 --> 00:42:54.190
Dry conditions in
the mass grave,

00:42:54.190 --> 00:42:55.830
which had been a brick kiln,

00:42:55.830 --> 00:42:59.570
had preserved the written order
sentencing Torekul Aitmatov,

00:42:59.570 --> 00:43:02.170
his father, Chingiz's, to death.

00:43:02.170 --> 00:43:05.970
The excavation of the mass
grave captivated Soviet Kyrgyzia

00:43:05.970 --> 00:43:07.960
during the Summer of 1991.

00:43:07.960 --> 00:43:12.860
And I'm going to show you a
little bit of a video here.

00:43:16.050 --> 00:43:19.380
So this is a video that
was taken by the people

00:43:19.380 --> 00:43:21.710
who were excavating
the grave and pulling

00:43:21.710 --> 00:43:25.450
out these skulls, 137.

00:43:25.450 --> 00:43:30.270
Pulling out personal
objects that were preserved

00:43:30.270 --> 00:43:35.970
in the climate, this
warm climate.

00:43:37.200 --> 00:43:39.500
These are shoes.

00:43:43.260 --> 00:43:47.000
This is the brick kiln that
became the burial ground.

00:43:56.040 --> 00:43:58.840
Here are other artifacts.

00:44:01.050 --> 00:44:04.730
This all happened
in July of 1991,

00:44:04.730 --> 00:44:07.000
six months before the
collapse of the Soviet Union.

00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:20.630
So here you can see in his
kalpak the worker is digging.

00:44:20.630 --> 00:44:24.480
And here they're
pulling out the letters.

00:44:24.480 --> 00:44:27.630
These are the sentencing
documents that preserved

00:44:27.630 --> 00:44:31.460
that had the names of the
people who were executed

00:44:31.460 --> 00:44:36.070
and then they were able to
match the bodies to the people

00:44:36.070 --> 00:44:37.620
and they were able
to tell relatives

00:44:37.620 --> 00:44:41.850
who had waited 53 years that
they had found the remains

00:44:41.850 --> 00:44:47.590
of their fathers,
brothers, husbands.

00:44:47.590 --> 00:44:53.360
So that gives you a sense.

00:44:53.360 --> 00:44:56.150
Aitmatov himself gave
voice to the miracle --

00:44:56.150 --> 00:44:57.850
so this is from the book --

00:44:57.850 --> 00:45:00.850
this is a quote e from
Chingiz Aitmatov --

00:45:00.850 --> 00:45:03.050
"Everything disappeared,
disintegrated,

00:45:03.050 --> 00:45:05.990
the bodies of the unfortunate
people, their shoes, clothes,"

00:45:05.990 --> 00:45:09.580
Aitmatov would say a few weeks
later, "except this paper,

00:45:09.580 --> 00:45:11.780
this document from
that era, with the name

00:45:11.780 --> 00:45:19.340
of Torekul Aitmatov, which
remained intact enough to read."

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:21.550
Dry conditions had
preserved the documents,

00:45:21.550 --> 00:45:24.580
but the Aitmatov family know
that something else was at work

00:45:24.580 --> 00:45:26.770
in solving the gruesome mystery.

00:45:26.770 --> 00:45:29.380
And so did many other Kyrgyz.

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:31.610
"There is in the world
some higher justice.

00:45:31.610 --> 00:45:32.910
"There is in the world
some higher justice,

00:45:32.910 --> 00:45:34.210
timeless, and absolute."

00:45:34.210 --> 00:45:37.190
Aitmatov said, "something maybe
beyond our everyday existence."

00:45:37.190 --> 00:45:39.730
Loss, redemption, and
hope, a true story

00:45:39.730 --> 00:45:43.510
of the Cold War from
Central Asia.

