00:46:13.650 --> 00:46:20.590
&gt;&gt; I didn't ask of this, Jeff,
but how did you come to decide

00:46:20.590 --> 00:46:25.290
to write about [inaudible],
both of them on one book.

00:46:25.290 --> 00:46:28.160
They have own books and stories.

00:46:29.740 --> 00:46:35.550
It was very [inaudible]
managed to tell the stories

00:46:35.550 --> 00:46:39.530
of two great men in one book.

00:46:39.530 --> 00:46:41.680
&gt;&gt; Jeffrey Lilley: I initially
wanted to write a biography

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:46.430
of Aitmatov because I really
liked his writing and I thought

00:46:46.430 --> 00:46:47.990
that this is writer

00:46:47.990 --> 00:46:50.600
that actually Americans
should know about.

00:46:50.600 --> 00:46:55.470
So that was the original idea
and I didn't find any biography

00:46:55.470 --> 00:46:56.900
of Aitmatov in English.

00:46:56.900 --> 00:46:59.920
And so that's what I started
out for three years doing

00:46:59.920 --> 00:47:04.720
and then I was interviewing
[inaudible] from Radio Liberty

00:47:04.720 --> 00:47:08.390
and he -- I was interviewing
him about Aitmatov

00:47:08.390 --> 00:47:10.140
and he mentioned Altay.

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:12.930
And I had never known -- I had
never heard of Altay's name.

00:47:12.930 --> 00:47:15.790
The whole time I was in
Kyrgyzstan for three years,

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:19.240
and he told me all about him and
I just thought wow, you know,

00:47:19.240 --> 00:47:21.890
that's a pretty interesting
story too and he was outside,

00:47:21.890 --> 00:47:24.280
Aitmatov was inside, and I
didn't know what I would find

00:47:24.280 --> 00:47:25.980
but I just -- it would
be more interesting --

00:47:25.980 --> 00:47:29.540
it was just a more interesting
story to me at that point.

00:47:29.540 --> 00:47:31.160
And as you as a formal
journalist,

00:47:31.160 --> 00:47:34.440
you know good stories are
important and weaving it.

00:47:34.440 --> 00:47:37.200
So I just then decided
to weave them,

00:47:37.200 --> 00:47:40.580
and then as I said the
other day, I think a writer,

00:47:40.580 --> 00:47:42.680
you have to be lucky too.

00:47:42.680 --> 00:47:44.750
And I was lucky because
I didn't know

00:47:44.750 --> 00:47:48.350
that they had met
in New York in 1975.

00:47:48.350 --> 00:47:49.650
I mean I think [inaudible]
said that,

00:47:49.650 --> 00:47:53.330
but then I found a letter
courtesy of [inaudible]

00:47:53.330 --> 00:47:56.940
that Altay wrote to a friend
after he had just met Aitmatov

00:47:56.940 --> 00:47:59.320
and he realized what
an important meeting

00:47:59.320 --> 00:48:00.680
that was for him.

00:48:00.680 --> 00:48:04.460
The photos were there and
then people were still alive,

00:48:04.460 --> 00:48:06.880
you know, and I could
get the story.

00:48:09.390 --> 00:48:11.190
Yes Mary-Jane?

00:48:11.190 --> 00:48:19.550
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:48:19.550 --> 00:48:23.140
&gt;&gt; Jeffrey Lilley: Yes, well
I'll tell you, as was mentioned

00:48:23.140 --> 00:48:28.680
in the film, Aitmatov lost a lot
of cousins and family members --

00:48:28.680 --> 00:48:30.580
three uncles, and I
can't even remember,

00:48:30.580 --> 00:48:32.480
and his father to the purges.

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:35.200
Of his own family,
there were four kids,

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:40.180
Chingiz was the oldest
and Ilgez was second,

00:48:40.180 --> 00:48:43.940
and Ilgez was a scientist, a
geologist, he's still alive.

00:48:43.940 --> 00:48:46.480
He was head of the
Academy of Sciences.

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:49.020
He was -- you know, worked

00:48:49.020 --> 00:48:52.320
in the geological
mining industry I think,

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:56.020
I'm not quite sure,
but he is about 80 --

00:48:56.020 --> 00:48:58.130
he must be 87 or something now.

00:48:58.130 --> 00:49:02.030
Because Chingiz would be 90,
so he's two years younger,

00:49:02.030 --> 00:49:03.370
88, distinguished man.

00:49:03.370 --> 00:49:07.260
And then Roza is alive
and well in Bishkek

00:49:07.260 --> 00:49:08.560
and she was the youngest.

00:49:08.560 --> 00:49:11.810
And she was nine months old
when her father disappeared.

00:49:11.810 --> 00:49:13.150
Never knew her father.

00:49:13.150 --> 00:49:14.870
She's written a bunch
of good books,

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:18.240
which have been very helpful,
about the family history.

00:49:18.240 --> 00:49:20.710
So she's alive and
well and was very --

00:49:20.710 --> 00:49:24.720
she was trained as a teacher
and very active in NGO work

00:49:24.720 --> 00:49:27.040
for many years after
independence.

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:30.170
And then, actually
Roza is youngest.

00:49:30.170 --> 00:49:38.350
Luzia was the third and Luzia
went to the Technical Institute

00:49:38.350 --> 00:49:40.700
and got a degree -- I can't
remember, in engineering.

00:49:40.700 --> 00:49:42.920
She died relatively young.

00:49:42.920 --> 00:49:44.480
I think in the mid '70s.

00:49:44.480 --> 00:49:46.630
But she was born as a twin.

00:49:46.630 --> 00:49:48.410
And there was a boy and a girl.

00:49:48.410 --> 00:49:50.660
Luzia was born and the boys name
was Revo [assumed spelling],

00:49:50.660 --> 00:49:54.850
so when you put it
together it's a Revo-Luzia,

00:49:54.850 --> 00:49:57.180
which shows you how
their parents

00:49:57.180 --> 00:50:03.100
where such committed
Communist to the cause.

00:50:03.100 --> 00:50:07.770
And yet the father gets
purged, you know, it's insanity.

00:50:07.770 --> 00:50:12.140
So she passed away but she
has a son, a couple of kids,

00:50:12.140 --> 00:50:16.170
and he is a writer and he has
written some interesting works

00:50:16.170 --> 00:50:19.800
about legacy of his uncle.

00:50:22.040 --> 00:50:28.880
Roza remained, Ilgez
remained, yes, and yeah.

00:50:28.880 --> 00:50:31.510
That's right.

00:50:31.510 --> 00:51:29.680
[ Inaudible Question ]

00:51:29.680 --> 00:51:31.940
&gt;&gt; Jeffrey Lilley: Right, I
mean, I think -- I don't know.

00:51:31.940 --> 00:51:38.680
I probably did 30, 40
interviews around the world --

00:51:38.680 --> 00:51:40.940
Europe, US., Kyrgyzstan.

00:51:40.940 --> 00:51:51.850
In terms of feedback, good
feedback, I was very gratified

00:51:51.850 --> 00:51:56.120
to get an email the other
day from the former president

00:51:56.120 --> 00:51:59.920
of Norton Publishing and
the former chairman emeritus

00:51:59.920 --> 00:52:03.970
of the Yale University Press,
one man, who was very helpful

00:52:03.970 --> 00:52:08.590
to me during the attempt
to find a publisher

00:52:08.590 --> 00:52:12.990
because I didn't write this
book having a publisher saying,

00:52:12.990 --> 00:52:15.970
"Jeff, we're going to
publish this book."

00:52:15.970 --> 00:52:21.070
So it was, I was I had to go out
and market it and as they say,

00:52:21.070 --> 00:52:25.550
you only need one person to
say yes, but a lot do say no.

00:52:25.550 --> 00:52:29.590
So his name is -- well,
it's not important --

00:52:29.590 --> 00:52:35.740
but he said something to
the effect of "History told

00:52:35.740 --> 00:52:39.320
at its best, narratives, scope,

00:52:39.320 --> 00:52:42.880
pace" and that was
really gratifying.

00:52:42.880 --> 00:52:46.190
I think, yeah, the other
people I've talked to --

00:52:46.190 --> 00:52:48.250
I haven't been back to the
states since it was published,

00:52:48.250 --> 00:52:53.060
I just got back four days ago,
have found it to be a good read,

00:52:53.060 --> 00:52:59.990
a page turner, you know, yeah
and educating them about a part

00:52:59.990 --> 00:53:01.660
of the world they may not
have known much about.

00:53:01.660 --> 00:53:04.860
But I think the thing
that I hope connects is

00:53:04.860 --> 00:53:06.490
that these are two
human individuals

00:53:06.490 --> 00:53:09.010
and it's actually
a universal story

00:53:09.010 --> 00:53:14.960
that transcends geography
or state borders.

00:53:14.960 --> 00:53:17.510
Yes?

00:53:17.510 --> 00:53:27.790
